TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$v0 = random(40,100,5);
$t0 = random(1,2,1);

BEGIN_TEXT
If a ball is thrown straight up into the air with an initial velocity of 
\( $v0 \) ft/s, its height in feet after \( t \) seconds is given by 
\( y = y(t) = $v0 t - 16 t^2 \).  $BR$BR$BR

$BBOLD a.) $EBOLD Find the average velocity for the time period beginning when \( t = $t0 \) and lasting for the given amount of time.  $BR$BR

$BITALIC (i) $EITALIC \( \Delta t= .5 \) seconds. $BR

Answer: \{ans_rule(35) \} $BR$BR

$BITALIC (ii)$EITALIC \( \Delta t = 0.1 \) seconds. $BR
Answer: \{ans_rule(35)  \} $BR$BR

$BITALIC (iii) $EITALIC \(\Delta t =  0.01 \) seconds. $BR
Answer: \{ans_rule(35)  \} $BR$BR

$BBOLD b.) $EBOLD Based on the above results, along with using even smaller values of \(\Delta t\), make an educated guess what the instantaneous
velocity of the ball is when \( t =$t0 \) seconds.  $BR
Answer: \{ans_rule(20) \} $BR
(Hint: the answer is an integer)

$PAR $HR $PAR

\{ theresahint\}
END_TEXT


BEGIN_HINT
Average rate of change converges to instantaneous rate, as the difference in time  goes to 0.

$PAR

Average rates of change are slopes of secant lines.  So we're computing slopes of lines through two points, with both points living on a curve.  One point comes from the fixed time-point of interest \(t_0\), the other from the time at duration \(\Delta t\) from \(t_0\).

$PAR

\(t_0\) is used to generate the first point, so evaluate the height function at \(t_0\).  The second time, at distance \(\Delta t\) from \(t_0\), is used to generate the second point, also via the height function.  Then, use \(\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta t}\) to compute the value.



